# error-boundary

## Intent
A single failing async component, broken data fetch, or unexpected runtime error must never take down the entire page.
Fault isolation is a structural requirement, not a defensive afterthought.

## What Requires Isolation

Any section that meets one or more of these criteria:

- Renders data from an external API, database, or Server Action
- Uses `Suspense` or `async` Server Components
- Is optional / non-critical to the core page function
- Has a realistic failure mode (e.g. third-party widget, user-generated content)
- Is below the fold or conditionally rendered

## Required Behavior

- MUST wrap qualifying sections in a React `error.tsx` boundary (App Router) or a custom `ErrorBoundary` component.
- MUST provide a meaningful fallback UI — not just `null`. Minimum: a message indicating the section failed to load, with a retry affordance if applicable.
- MUST use `Suspense` with a loading fallback for async Server Components.
- If a shared `<FaultIsolatedSection>` component does not yet exist in `@vibe/ui`, MUST add a `{/* FAULT-ISOLATION-PENDING */}` comment at the wrapping point and note what the fallback behavior should be.
- For pages with multiple independent data-fetching sections, MUST isolate each section independently — a single `error.tsx` at the layout level is not sufficient.

## FAULT-ISOLATION-PENDING Comment Format

```tsx
{/* FAULT-ISOLATION-PENDING: wrap with <FaultIsolatedSection> when @vibe/ui is ready */}
{/* Fallback: show "Unable to load recent activity" with retry button */}
<RecentActivityPanel />
```

## Forbidden Behavior

- MUST NOT leave async data-fetching components unwrapped at the page root without a granular error boundary.
- MUST NOT use `try/catch` that silently swallows errors and renders nothing — always render a fallback.
- MUST NOT treat a top-level `layout.tsx` error boundary as sufficient coverage for all nested dynamic sections.
- MUST NOT throw from a Server Component without a corresponding `error.tsx` in the same route segment.

## Good Example

```tsx
// app/dashboard/page.tsx
export default function DashboardPage() {
  return (
    <main>
      <HeroStats />  {/* static, no isolation needed */}

      <Suspense fallback={<RecentOrdersSkeleton />}>
        <ErrorBoundary fallback={<ErrorCard message="Orders failed to load" />}>
          <RecentOrders />
        </ErrorBoundary>
      </Suspense>

      <Suspense fallback={<ActivityFeedSkeleton />}>
        <ErrorBoundary fallback={<ErrorCard message="Activity unavailable" />}>
          <ActivityFeed />
        </ErrorBoundary>
      </Suspense>
    </main>
  )
}
```

## Bad Example

```tsx
// FORBIDDEN: one error.tsx at layout level covers everything — if RecentOrders
// throws, ActivityFeed never renders either
export default function DashboardPage() {
  return (
    <main>
      <HeroStats />
      <RecentOrders />
      <ActivityFeed />
    </main>
  )
}
```

## Notes

- App Router `error.tsx` files handle Server Component errors. Client Component errors still require a React `ErrorBoundary` class component or a library wrapper.
- Skeleton loaders count as valid Suspense fallbacks for Phase 1–2. Elaborate empty states are a later concern.
- Static sections (no async, no external data) do not need isolation.
